  "articleSummary": "This article critically examines common Promise anti-patterns in popular JavaScript documentation and libraries, arguing that practices like the `deferred` pattern unnecessarily complicate asynchronous code without offering meaningful advantages over traditional callbacks. Analyzing examples from CallbackHell.com, StrongLoop, RisingStack, and the legacy Q library, the author adopts a reflective, code-review tone to highlight warning signs and advocate for cleaner functional patterns. Framed around the \"callback mountain\" metaphor, the piece targets JavaScript developers seeking to standardize and improve their async coding practices and documentation standards. The author concludes by directing readers to a companion GitHub repository for practical, modern alternatives.",
